Dutch newspapers reported that on August 7 1954  Captain Jan P. Boshoff (in the book his name was spelled Bos) of the SS Groote Beer, who was a very respected captain with 41 years of experience at sea, saw a strange, flat, ‚Äúmoonlike‚Äù object rise out of the ocean, eighty or ninety miles east of Cape Cod. Through binoculars, he saw clearly illuminated ports on the rim. The object then moved at a "fantastic" speed. In vertical motion and flew above the meridian. Disappeared in some clouds vanished at14.000km. Boshoff was not the only person. His crew and many passengers saw it. He even was on American TV when he docked. He said he never had seen such an event in his life.
When he returned to Holland he was all over the news. I realised that in 1954 the ridicule machine had not done his job yet. A captain was always considered credible. 
Today a captain would keep his mouth shut out of fear for his career. This is what years of ridicule has done to people.
When Hynek investigated this later on in project bluebook, he realised that an american citizen on land reported a UFO above sea at the exact time at the exact location. Now that was what I call double evidence!

I was in Iraq on a Bradley Fighting Vehicle in 2004 when we were sitting on a screenline outside of town and city limits. Late one night, an airborne object appeared in the sights and we lazed it at 5 clicks. It then moved rapidly back and forth, left and right (just as these Navy pilots observed) at a high rate of speed and change in direction ranging from 5km to 20km.
